# Extension Configuration File (extension.toml) Rules

This document outlines the rules and best practices for writing and maintaining `extension.toml` files in the Isaac Sim repository.

## File Location

- Every extension must have an `extension.toml` file located in the `config` directory of the extension.
- Example path: `source/extensions/<extension-name>/config/extension.toml`

## Section Ordering

Sections in `extension.toml` files should appear in the following order to maintain consistency across the codebase:

1. `[core]` - Core extension properties
2. `[package]` - Package metadata
3. `[deprecation]` - Deprecation information (if applicable)
4. `[dependencies]` - Extension dependencies
5. `[[python.module]]` - Python module definitions
6. `[[native.library]]` - Native library paths (if needed)
7. `[[python.pipapi]]` - Python package requirements for the extension (if needed)
8. `[[native.plugin]]` - Native plugin definitions (if needed)
9. `[settings]` - Extension-specific settings (if needed)
10. `[[trigger]]` - Extension triggers/menu items (if needed)
11. `[[fswatcher.patterns]]` - File system watcher patterns (if needed)
12. `[[fswatcher.paths]]` - File system watcher path exclusions (if needed)
13. `[[test]]` - Test configuration (if needed)
14. `[documentation]` - Documentation pages (if needed)

The required sections must be present and in the correct order. Optional sections should be included in the specified order when needed.

## Spacing Requirements

- Each section should be preceded by exactly one blank line (not more, not less).
- No extra blank lines at the start of the file; at the end of the file, 0 or 1 empty line is acceptable (not more).
- Section headers that immediately follow comments do not require a blank line between the comment and the header.
- Multiple array sections of the same type (e.g., multiple `[[python.module]]` sections) should be separated by exactly one blank line.

## Required Sections

### 1. [core] Section

```toml
[core]
reloadable = true  # Whether the extension can be reloaded at runtime
order = 0          # Load order priority (lower values are loaded first)
```

### 2. [package] Section

Fields in the `[package]` section must appear in this order (enforced by the validator):

```toml
[package]
version = "x.y.z"                # Semantic version (required)
category = "Category"            # Extension category (e.g., "Simulation", "Rendering")
title = "Extension Title"        # Human-readable title
description = "Description..."   # Clear description of what the extension does
authors = ["email@nvidia.com"]   # List of author emails
repository = "https://..."       # Repository URL for the extension
keywords = ["keyword1", "keyword2"] # Keywords for search/categorization
changelog = "docs/CHANGELOG.md"  # Path to changelog file
readme = "docs/README.md"        # Path to readme file
preview_image = "data/preview.png" # Path to preview image
icon = "data/icon.png"           # Path to icon image
writeTarget.kit = true           # Target platforms (optional)
writeTarget.platform = true      # Platform-specific targets (optional)
feature = true                   # Feature flag (optional)
deprecation = true               # Deprecation flag (optional)
```

### 3. [deprecation] Section (if applicable)

```toml
[deprecation]
warning = "Extension deprecated since Isaac Sim X.Y.Z. Replaced by isaacsim.replacement.extension."
```

### 4. [dependencies] Section

```toml
[dependencies]
"dependency.alpha" = {}          # Required dependency
"dependency.beta" = { optional = true } # Optional dependency
"dependency.gamma" = {}          # Another required dependency
```

All dependencies should be sorted alphabetically by name to maintain consistency and make it easier to find specific dependencies.

### 5. Python Module Section

```toml
[[python.module]]
name = "module.name"             # Name of the Python module to expose
```

## Optional Sections

### 6. [[native.library]] Section

```toml
[[native.library]]
path = "lib/*.so"                # Path to native library files
recursive = false                # Whether to search recursively
```

### 7. [[python.pipapi]] Section

```toml
[[python.pipapi]]
requirements = [
    "package-name==1.0.0"
]
```

### 8. [[native.plugin]] Section

```toml
[[native.plugin]]
path = "bin/*.plugin"            # Path to native plugin files
recursive = false                # Whether to search recursively
```

### 9. [settings] Section

```toml
[settings]
exts."extension.name".setting_name = value # Extension-specific settings
```

Each setting in the [settings] section MUST have a descriptive comment above it explaining its purpose and expected values. Platform-specific settings sections (e.g. `[settings."filter:platform=linux*"]`) are allowed and are treated as part of the settings group for section ordering.

### 10. [[trigger]] Section

```toml
[[trigger]]
menu.name = "Menu/Path"          # Menu path for the extension
menu.window = "Window Title"     # Window title for the extension
```

### 11. [[fswatcher.patterns]] Section

```toml
[[fswatcher.patterns]]
pattern = "*.ext"                # File pattern to watch
```

### 12. [[fswatcher.paths]] Section

```toml
[[fswatcher.paths]]
path = "path/to/exclude"         # Path to exclude from watching
```

### 13. [[test]] Section

Fields within each `[[test]]` block must appear in this order (enforced by the validator): `name`, `timeout`, `dependencies`, `args`, `stdoutFailPatterns.exclude`, `stdoutFailPatterns.include`.

```toml
[[test]]
name = "optional_test_name"  # Optional: Name for the test case
timeout = 300                    # Test timeout in seconds
dependencies = [                 # Dependencies required for tests
    "test.dependency.alpha",
    "test.dependency.beta",
    "test.dependency.gamma",
]
args = [                         # Command-line arguments for the test
    "--argument1=value1",
]
stdoutFailPatterns.exclude = [   # Patterns to exclude from failure detection
    "*pattern to ignore*",
]
stdoutFailPatterns.include = [   # Patterns to include in failure detection (optional)
    "*pattern to match*",
]
```

The dependencies listed in the `dependencies` array of each `[[test]]` section must be sorted alphabetically for consistency and easier maintenance.

Test sections have specific ordering requirements:
- The `name = "startup"` test section must appear first among all test sections.
- There must be at most one unnamed test section per extension.toml file.
- After "startup", other named test sections must appear in alphabetical order by their `name` field; the single unnamed section (if present) must come last.
- Named test sections should have a `name` field that uniquely identifies the test.

Example of proper test section ordering:
```toml
[[test]]
name = "startup"  # "startup" test section must be first
args = [
    "--arg1=value1",
]

[[test]]
name = "other_test"  # Other named sections in alphabetical order by name
args = [
    "--arg3=value3",
]

[[test]]  # Unnamed section last (at most one allowed)
args = [
    "--arg2=value2",
]
```

### 14. [documentation] Section

```toml
[documentation]
pages = [                        # Documentation pages
    "docs/Overview.md",
    "docs/CHANGELOG.md",
]
```

## Best Practices

1. **Section Ordering**:
   - Always follow the prescribed section order for consistency
   - Group related settings together within their respective sections
   - Keep exactly one blank line between sections
   - Avoid extra blank lines at the start of the file; at most one blank line at end of file

2. **Alphabetical Ordering**:
   - All dependencies in the [dependencies] section must be alphabetically sorted
   - All dependencies in the dependencies list of the [[test]] section must be alphabetically sorted
   - Alphabetical ordering makes it easier to find specific dependencies and avoids duplicate entries

3. **Deprecation**:
   - Use the [deprecation] section for extensions that are being phased out
   - Always include a warning message with the deprecation version and replacement extension
   - Deprecated extensions should maintain minimal dependencies

4. **Version Numbers**:
   - Follow semantic versioning (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH)
   - Ensure the version in `extension.toml` matches the latest version in the changelog

5. **Authors**:
   - Authors should be listed with their email addresses
   - The CODEOWNERS file is automatically generated from extension.toml author lists

6. **Documentation**:
   - Always include a README.md and CHANGELOG.md
   - Keep the changelog up to date with each version change

7. **Dependencies**:
   - Only list direct dependencies
   - Mark dependencies as optional when appropriate
   - Use empty object notation `{}` for required dependencies
   - Keep dependencies alphabetically sorted for consistency

8. **Testing**:
   - Include appropriate test sections with necessary dependencies
   - Specify any required arguments for testing
   - List patterns to exclude from failure detection when needed
   - Keep test dependencies alphabetically sorted

9. **Metadata**:
   - Provide clear, concise descriptions
   - Include relevant keywords for search/categorization
   - Use appropriate category labels

10. **Visual Assets**:
    - Include preview images and icons when possible
    - Keep visual assets in the `data` directory

11. **Settings**:
    - Use namespaced settings with the extension name
    - Document each setting with clear comments above it
    - Ensure each setting has a descriptive comment explaining its purpose

12. **Reloadability**:
    - Set `reloadable = true` only if the extension can truly be reloaded at runtime

13. **Load Order**:
    - Use appropriate order values to ensure correct loading sequence
    - Lower values are loaded first (0 is default priority, negative is higher, positive is lower priority) 

## Validation

The repository includes a validation tool at `tools/isaac/validate_extension_toml.py` that can be used to check for compliance with these rules and automatically fix common issues:

- Run without arguments to validate all `extension.toml` files in the repository
- Use `--fix-whitespace` to fix spacing between sections and file boundaries (allows 0 or 1 empty line at EOF)
- Use `--fix-section-order` to fix the order of sections and of `[[test]]` blocks (startup first, then named alphabetically, then unnamed)
- Use `--fix-package-order` to fix the order of fields in the `[package]` and `[[test]]` sections
- Use `--fix-dependencies-order` to fix alphabetical ordering of dependencies
- Use `--check-write-target` to add missing `writeTarget.kit = true` when needed
- Use `--fix` to apply all available fixes